SIMPLE: welter
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Welter
<hw>Wel"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Weltered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Weltering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Freq. of OE.
<ets>walten</ets> to roll over, AS. <ets>wealtan</ets>; akin to LG.
<ets>weltern</ets>, G. <ets>walzen</ets> to roll, to waltz, sich
<ets>w⟦aum⟧lzen</ets> to welter, OHG. <ets>walzan</ets> to roll, Icel.
<ets>velta</ets>, Dan. <ets>v⟦ae⟧lte</ets>, Sw. <ets>v⟦aum⟧ltra</ets>,
<ets>v⟦aum⟧lta</ets>; cf. Goth. <ets>waltjan</ets>; probably akin to E.
<ets>wallow</ets>, <ets>well</ets>, v. i. ⟦root⟧146. See <er>Well</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos>, and cf. <er>Waltz</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To roll, as the body of an animal; to tumble about,
especially in anything foul or defiling; to wallow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When we <qex>welter</qex> in pleasures and idleness, then we eat
and drink with drunkards.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These wizards <qex>welter</qex> in wealth's waves.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He must not float upon his watery bier⟦br⟧
Unwept, and <qex>welter</qex> to the parching wind,⟦br⟧
Without the meed of some melodious tear.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The priests at the altar . . . <qex>weltering</qex> in their
blood.</q> <rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To rise and fall, as waves; to tumble over, as
billows.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>weltering</xex> waves.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Waves that, hardly <qex>weltering</qex>, die away.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Through this blindly <qex>weltering</qex> sea.</q>
<rj><qau>Trench.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Welter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Welter
<hw>Wel"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Wilt</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <def>To wither; to wilt.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Weltered</qex> hearts and blighted . . . memories.</q>
<rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Welter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Welter
<hw>Wel"ter</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <fld>(Horse Racing)</fld> <def>Of,
pertaining to, or designating, the most heavily weighted race in a
meeting; <as>as, a <ex>welter</ex> race; the <ex>welter</ex>
stakes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Welter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Welter
<hw>Wel"ter</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>That in which any person or thing welters, or
wallows; filth; mire; slough.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The foul <qex>welter</qex> of our so-called religious or other
controversies.</q> <rj><qau>Carlyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A rising or falling, as of waves; <as>as, the
<ex>welter</ex> of the billows; the <ex>welter</ex> of a
tempest</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Welterweight</ent>⟦br⟧
